\begin{abstract}
We present a Hamiltonian Crystal framework in which the vacuum is a discrete lattice of Fock-space modes with integer spectral indices. The vacuum spectral gaps naturally generate neutrino masses via gauge-invariant portal couplings, while simultaneously producing a vacuum energy density consistent with the observed dark energy. The framework predicts a small logarithmic energy-dependent correction to neutrino oscillation probabilities, providing a falsifiable signature for long-baseline experiments. We include numerical simulations, predicted mass matrices, and a schematic of the crystal structure to guide experimental tests.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
Neutrino masses and the cosmological constant are two fundamental puzzles. Observed neutrino oscillations require non-zero masses, while cosmology indicates a small vacuum energy density. 

We propose both phenomena arise from a discrete Hamiltonian Crystal structure in vacuum: a lattice of Fock-space modes with spectral gaps $\Delta E_n$ that couple to Standard Model leptons via gauge-invariant portals. This structure links neutrino properties and vacuum energy while predicting experimentally testable deviations in oscillation probabilities.

\section{Hamiltonian Crystal Spectrum and Couplings}
The crystal consists of modes $\phi_n$ labeled by integer $n$:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{HC} =
\sum_n \left( \partial_\mu \phi_n^\dagger \partial^\mu \phi_n - \Delta E_n^2 \phi_n^\dagger \phi_n \right),
\end{equation}
with Lorentz invariance. The spectral gaps:
\begin{equation}
\Delta E_n = \Lambda \log(n), \quad n\ge2,
\end{equation}
provide discrete ``ticks'' for vacuum excitations.

Standard Model lepton doublets $L_i=(\nu_i,e_i)^T$ couple via:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{portal} = \sum_{i,n} g_{in} (\bar{L}_i H) \phi_n + h.c.
\end{equation}
After EWSB $\langle H \rangle = v/\sqrt{2}$, Dirac-type neutrino masses arise:
\begin{equation}
(M_\nu)_{ij} = \sum_n \frac{g_{in} g_{jn} v^2}{2 \Delta E_n}.
\end{equation}

